# 3k-docs content reuse

`3k-docs/` has historically been a parallel tree of thin wrapper pages that do not contain real content — each one imports and renders a component from `docs/` (or occasionally `src/components/`). **That is no longer true of every module.** Modules are being incrementally cleaned out and rewritten with real, hand-authored content directly in `3k-docs/`, because page-by-page import-fixing is not viable once too much has drifted (Continuous Delivery is the first, cut 2026-07-20; Harness AI, Platform, and FME are planned next). Go to **Wrapper pages vs. rewritten modules** below to determine which rule applies to a given file before editing it.

The legacy wrapper pattern:

```mdx
---
title: CI Supported Platforms
---

import Ci from '@site/docs/continuous-integration/ci-supported-platforms.md';

<Ci />
```

Frontmatter (`title`, `description`, `sidebar_position`, etc.) is independent per file and owned by the `3k-docs/` page. Only the **body** is reused via the import. `scripts/convert-3k-docs.mjs` is the generator that originally produced this wrapper pattern for a module.

## Rule

Whenever you **move**, **rename**, or **delete** a file under `docs/` or `src/components/`, check whether any `3k-docs/` file imports it, and fix the import as part of the same change — do not leave it for CI to catch.

1. **Find importers of the old path:**
   ```bash
   grep -rn "@site/docs/<old-relative-path>" 3k-docs/
   grep -rn "@site/src/<old-relative-path>" 3k-docs/
   ```
   (Drop the file extension when searching component paths — `import Foo from '@site/src/components/Docs/Foo'` has no `.tsx` suffix.)

2. **Simple rename/move (content unchanged, just relocated):** Rewrite the import statement to the new path. That is the entire fix — do not touch the rest of the wrapper file.

3. **Content split, merged, or restructured (not a 1:1 rename):** There is no mechanical fix. Read what the `3k-docs/` page needs and either point it at the correct single source, add a second `import`/render if the content now lives in two files, or regenerate the wrapper for the whole module with `node scripts/convert-3k-docs.mjs <module-path> <component-name>`. This is what the CCM `legacy/`-prefix cases and the restored `HsuCalculator` component needed in the 2026-07-16 incident — a plain path swap wasn't enough.

4. **File deleted outright with no replacement:** Decide with the page owner whether the `3k-docs/` wrapper should be deleted too, inlined with real content (see `docs/platform/rbac/*` for an example of a page that was deliberately de-linked from the import pattern and given inline content instead), or repointed elsewhere. Do not leave a dangling import.

## Also check sidebars-3k-docs.ts

`sidebars-3k-docs.ts` is the `3k-docs/` tree's own sidebar config, and it has the same manual/autogenerated duality already documented for `sidebars.ts` in CLAUDE.md's "Sidebar Navigation Configuration":

- **Manual doc-ID references:** `link: { type: 'doc', id: 'platform/getting-started/index' }`. This `id` is a path under `3k-docs/` (without extension). If you move or rename the `3k-docs/` file it points to, update the `id` to match.
- **Autogenerated category references:** `items: [{ type: 'autogenerated', dirName: 'code-repository/config-repos' }]`. This `dirName` is a folder path under `3k-docs/`. If you rename or move that folder, update `dirName` to match.

Whenever you move, rename, or delete a file or folder under `3k-docs/`, grep `sidebars-3k-docs.ts` for the old path in both forms before you finish the change:

```bash
grep -n "id: '<old-path-without-extension>'" sidebars-3k-docs.ts
grep -n "dirName: '<old-folder-path>'" sidebars-3k-docs.ts
```

Update every match to the new path in the same change. A stale `id` or `dirName` fails the build the same way a stale `@site/...` import does, just through a different code path (the sidebar plugin cannot resolve the doc or folder it points to).

Note: `scripts/check-3k-docs-drift.mjs` only checks `id:` and `dirName:` keyed references, plus it ignores anything inside a `//` or `/* */` comment (this file has large commented-out sidebar blocks for retired modules). It does not check bare doc-ID strings used directly as sidebar array items (e.g. `'platform/fme-support'`) — those still need a manual grep if you rename a file referenced that way.

## Wrapper pages vs. rewritten modules

Not every file under `3k-docs/` follows the import-reuse pattern anymore. Before applying the Rule above, check which model the file uses:

- **Wrapper page:** the file's body is (or should be) just `import X from '@site/docs/...'; <X />`. This is still the default for any module that has not been rewritten. The **Rule** section above governs moves, renames, and deletions.
- **Rewritten (hand-authored) page:** the file has no `@site/...` import and instead contains real Markdown/MDX content written directly for `3k-docs/`. Once a module is rewritten this way, moving or renaming a file inside it is a normal doc move, governed by **[Doc Moves: Redirects and Link Updates](mdc:doc-move.mdc)**, not the import-sync rule — there is no import to fix because there never was one.

`scripts/check-3k-docs-drift.mjs` needs no special-casing for this distinction: it only ever flags files it finds an `@site/...` import in, so a hand-authored page with no import is silently skipped, never a false positive. The `sidebars-3k-docs.ts` `id:`/`dirName:` check above still applies uniformly to both kinds of pages — the sidebar plugin only cares about file paths on disk, not about how the content got there.

## Content-parity reminders for rewritten modules

`3k-docs-module-status.json` at the repo root is the source of truth for which top-level modules are `rewritten` (hand-authored) versus still the default wrapper pattern. When you rewrite a module (as with Continuous Delivery), add its top-level directory name to the `rewritten` array in that file — this is what drives the reminder below.

Once a module is `rewritten`, docs/ and its 3k-docs/ counterpart are two independently maintained surfaces by design — content is expected to diverge, not stay identical. But some changes to docs/ (a corrected step, a security-relevant caveat, a renamed field) are the kind that should probably land in both places. `scripts/check-3k-docs-drift.mjs` checks this: if a PR changes `docs/<rewritten-module>/X.md` and `3k-docs/<rewritten-module>/X.md` exists but was not touched in the same PR, it prints a **non-blocking** reminder ("content-parity reminder") and never fails the build over it. Treat this as a nudge to go check whether the rewritten copy needs the same update, not as drift to fix mechanically — often the right answer is "no, this doesn't apply on the rewritten page," and that's fine.

**Known gap, verified against `docusaurus.config.ts`:** the `redirect_from` frontmatter mechanism (`scanDocsForPathsAndRedirects`, feeding `@docusaurus/plugin-client-redirects`) only walks `docsDir` (`docs/`) and hardcodes `/docs/${pathId}` as the canonical path. It does not scan `3k-docs/` at all, so `redirect_from` set on a hand-authored `3k-docs/` page today is inert — it will not generate a working redirect, even though nothing fails the build to warn you. Once a module has real content and its own internal moves (like the CD restructuring), old `/3k-docs/...` URLs pointing at moved/removed pages will silently 404 instead of redirecting. This needs a fix in `docusaurus.config.ts` (either generalize `scanDocsForPathsAndRedirects` to also walk the `3k-docs/` directory with its own `/3k-docs/` path prefix, or add a second, parallel scan) before relying on `redirect_from` for a rewritten module's internal restructuring. Flag this to whoever owns `docusaurus.config.ts` before or during a module rewrite.

## Why this matters

An `@site/docs/...` or `@site/src/...` import that points at a path which no longer exists fails `docusaurus build` (`onBrokenLinks: 'throw'`) with a module-not-found error. This is exactly what happened in the HDH-561 incident: a docs/ page move shipped without updating the matching `3k-docs/` import, the build broke on merge to `main`, and every subsequent PR's preview build failed until someone traced ~22 stale imports by hand.

A stale `id`/`dirName` in `sidebars-3k-docs.ts` breaks the build the same way, via the same `onBrokenLinks: 'throw'` config, when the sidebar plugin resolves it against a path that no longer exists.

`scripts/check-3k-docs-drift.mjs` runs in CI as a backstop — it auto-fixes clean renames (both `@site/...` imports and `sidebars-3k-docs.ts` `id:` entries) and fails the build on anything ambiguous, including `dirName:` folder renames, which it always flags for a human rather than guessing — but it is a safety net, not the first line of defense. Fixing the import or sidebar reference in the same PR that moves the file means the check passes silently instead of failing and blocking the build.

## When to apply

- You move, rename, or delete a file under `docs/` (any depth).
- You move, rename, or delete a component under `src/components/`.
- You move, rename, or delete a file or folder under `3k-docs/` itself.
- You split one doc into several, or merge several into one.
- You are asked to regenerate or clean up `3k-docs/` wrappers for a module.
